djmfiel 27-Aug-20 07:12 AM
I want to clarify something regarding the translation before the proofreaders had the chance to finish the work(I believe the proofreading was just assigned). It seems me and @cloudfiel is working on this and I wanted to keep some terms consistent. I didn't use the term '형님'(heong) or anything similar to that because I believed the reader would be unfamiliar with it. It was my personal view that there would be not much redeeming value in using a term that requires a footnote to understand and yet not integral for the understanding of the story.
I want to make the translation of such terms like '형님', '누나','오빠' consistent to make life easier for the translators and especially for the translators. I went with the approach of not using it or just using Mr. (Name). On my review of the translations I noticed that cloud used the Romanized version of the term.
I think translators me( @djmfiel ) and cloud( @cloudfiel ) and proofreaders Suzuran ( @Suzuran ) and Lunar( @Georgiel [Holy Trinity] *Hiatus* ) are in this project.
I am hoping to get clarification or advice regarding the translations of the terms I mentioned.
I believe this will contribute to making the overall work more consistent.

djmfiel 04-Sep-20 08:24 PM
system nani
@pumpkingfiel The romanization system refers to a way to convert Korean into English form. The two main dilemmas with romanization involves either to preserve the pronunciation or to preserve the one to one correspondence with the spelling of the word itself. To my knowledge the McCune–Reischauer romanization(created in 1937) is primarily about the pronunciation and it takes into account the various phonological variation and attempts to show it with various signs like apostrophe(') or breve(˘). The Yale romanization system(created in 1942) is mainly concerned with preserving the form of the language. So to my knowledge you can go back and forth with the Romanized form and the original word itself. Because to my knowledge there is a one to one correspondence relationship. Because of that I heard that it is primarily used in linguistics. The Revised Romanization system(created in 2000) tries to compromise both approaches and it mainly tries to keep the correspondence with the original word but in some cases it does take account for phonological variations. It is the official system used by the Korean government. This is all just approximate pumpkin, and I am not a person with a linguistical background so bear in mind it may not be that accurate. I hope it was somewhat helpful.
